                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 811.0144/14.</note>
                <head ana="#head_untitled-inferred-from-preceding-sibling-head">[Untitled]</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Mexico City</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-01-31T21:00:00-06:36">
                            <hi rend="italic">January 31, 1914, 9 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>756. I transmit herewith a translation of the note addressed to the Minister for
                    Foreign Affairs by the Minister of War and Marine: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>In reply to your note No. 549 of to-day requesting that orders be given
                            to the end that Samuel Cantu be set at liberty I have the honor to
                            inform you that telegraphic orders were to-day sent to General Quintana
                            to direct that Samuel Cantu be immediately set absolutely at liberty and
                            to report that this order has been complied with without any excuse or
                            pretext whatsoever. I have the honor to transmit this to you for your
                            information and such action as may be deemed appropriate. I avail myself
                            of this occasion [etc.]</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Nelson O’Shaughnessy</hi>
                    </signed>.</closer>
            </div>
        </body>
